1
00:02:23,560 --> 00:02:29,799
Our God is marching on

2
00:02:29,800 --> 00:02:34,839
Glory, glory, hallelujah

3
00:02:34,840 --> 00:02:39,599
Glory, glory, hallelujah

4
00:02:39,600 --> 00:02:43,799
Glory, glory, hallelujah

5
00:02:43,800 --> 00:02:49,039
His truth is marching on

6
00:02:49,040 --> 00:02:54,319
In the beauty of the lilies
Christ was born across the sea

7
00:02:54,320 --> 00:02:59,239
With a glory in His bosom
that transfigures you and me

8
00:02:59,240 --> 00:03:04,239
As He died to make men holy,
let us die to make men free

9
00:03:04,240 --> 00:03:09,559
While God is marching on

10
00:03:09,560 --> 00:03:14,599
Glory, glory, hallelujah

11
00:03:14,600 --> 00:03:19,439
Glory, glory, hallelujah

12
00:03:19,440 --> 00:03:23,759
Glory, glory, hallelujah

13
00:03:23,760 --> 00:03:30,239
His truth is marching on

14
00:03:30,240 --> 00:03:33,760
Please be seated.

15
00:03:34,800 --> 00:03:37,639
Chuck always said to me,
"Wilbur...

16
00:03:37,640 --> 00:03:39,919
you talk too much".

17
00:03:39,920 --> 00:03:42,519
So he'd be pleased
that his beloved daughter, Marie,

18
00:03:42,520 --> 00:03:46,360
is going to say a few words.

19
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:03,159
I know that daddy
would be very pleased to see

20
00:04:03,160 --> 00:04:05,279
so many veterans here today.

21
00:04:05,280 --> 00:04:10,559
Especially members of
the 401st Bomber Group.

22
00:04:10,560 --> 00:04:14,720
I guess he would want to talk

23
00:04:15,560 --> 00:04:19,319
I guess he would want me
to talk about his life...

24
00:04:19,320 --> 00:04:22,639
...and about the most
important thing in his life,

25
00:04:22,640 --> 00:04:26,159
his love for my mother.

26
00:04:26,160 --> 00:04:30,559
He was a brave man
in wartime in his lifetime,

27
00:04:30,560 --> 00:04:36,040
and in the long illness
that led to his death.

28
00:04:36,480 --> 00:04:40,039
But his was an unspoken bravery.

29
00:04:40,040 --> 00:04:46,079
His heroism was as quiet
and as constant as he was.

30
00:04:46,080 --> 00:04:49,960
Many loved him.

31
00:04:51,560 --> 00:04:54,039
You don't smoke.

32
00:04:54,040 --> 00:04:58,000
I thought I'd take it up again.

33
00:04:59,280 --> 00:05:01,439
You should be in there, you know.

34
00:05:01,440 --> 00:05:02,639
I know what she's gonna say.

35
00:05:02,640 --> 00:05:06,439
I just can't sit there and
listen to all of that.

36
00:05:06,440 --> 00:05:09,360
I understand.

37
00:05:16,080 --> 00:05:20,040
Only you would understand.

38
00:05:20,800 --> 00:05:22,159
I'm really sorry.

39
00:05:22,160 --> 00:05:23,319
No need to.

40
00:05:23,320 --> 00:05:25,079
It was his time to go.

41
00:05:25,080 --> 00:05:27,239
No, I mean about being late.

42
00:05:27,240 --> 00:05:33,440
I mean I'm sorry about that too,
I mean, about him...

43
00:05:35,840 --> 00:05:37,599
It's all gassed up, dad.

44
00:05:37,600 --> 00:05:38,999
It's ready to go.

45
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:40,080
Good.

46
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:44,239
Sure you want this?

47
00:05:44,240 --> 00:05:45,760
He would.

48
00:05:47,600 --> 00:05:50,399
You won't remember daddy
for what he said.

49
00:05:50,400 --> 00:05:54,079
As you know, he didn't say much.

50
00:05:54,080 --> 00:05:56,319
He never spoke to me
about the past,

51
00:05:56,320 --> 00:06:01,039
about the war and
about his medals.

52
00:06:01,040 --> 00:06:03,839
Not even once.

53
00:06:03,840 --> 00:06:07,399
He felt that a man should be
judged for his work...

54
00:06:07,400 --> 00:06:11,319
...and for the way
that he led his life.

55
00:06:11,320 --> 00:06:15,919
Marie will be upset that you
missed her eulogy.

56
00:06:15,920 --> 00:06:20,640
I don't think Marie cares
either way if I'm there.

57
00:06:21,280 --> 00:06:23,239
Your husband was a fine man.

58
00:06:23,240 --> 00:06:24,320
Yeah.

59
00:06:24,560 --> 00:06:25,919
You'll miss him very much.

60
00:06:25,920 --> 00:06:27,080
No.

61
00:06:28,680 --> 00:06:32,319
Well, I know you loved him, so

62
00:06:32,320 --> 00:06:34,199
He never believed that, Peter.

63
00:06:34,200 --> 00:06:41,000
All the years I wore this ring
we never talked much about love.

64
00:06:43,800 --> 00:06:46,599
Would you like me to
take you back inside?

65
00:06:46,600 --> 00:06:47,240
No.

66
00:06:47,480 --> 00:06:51,240
They'll roll him out
when they're through.

67
00:06:53,760 --> 00:06:57,640
At least he has a grave.

68
00:07:22,800 --> 00:07:24,360
Hello.

69
00:07:26,640 --> 00:07:27,400
Hello.

70
00:07:27,600 --> 00:07:30,719
Bloody hell!

71
00:07:30,720 --> 00:07:33,399
What the devil do you mean,
creeping up on me like that?

72
00:07:33,400 --> 00:07:34,799
What you digging for?

73
00:07:34,800 --> 00:07:36,559
Who the hell are you?

74
00:07:36,560 --> 00:07:37,920
I'm Jimmy.

75
00:07:39,080 --> 00:07:40,719
Eleanor Reilly's wee lad?

76
00:07:40,720 --> 00:07:42,079
I know you.

77
00:07:42,080 --> 00:07:43,959
She's my granny.

78
00:07:43,960 --> 00:07:49,720
My mum went away
she is back any time now.

79
00:07:50,280 --> 00:07:52,079
Does your granny know
you're up here?

80
00:07:52,080 --> 00:07:52,959
Don't know.

81
00:07:52,960 --> 00:07:54,319
Well, you go home

82
00:07:54,320 --> 00:07:57,679
Tell her Mr Quinlan said you're
not to come up here again.

83
00:07:57,680 --> 00:07:59,999
This is a dangerous place,
do you not know that?

84
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:01,359
The Army is here all the time.

85
00:08:01,360 --> 00:08:02,519
If it's not them,
it's the Republicans,

86
00:08:02,520 --> 00:08:04,079
the bloody IRA.

87
00:08:04,080 --> 00:08:05,399
So what are you doing here then?

88
00:08:05,400 --> 00:08:07,439
None of your bloody business!

89
00:08:07,440 --> 00:08:09,159
You're digging something.

90
00:08:09,160 --> 00:08:12,879
I dig here sometimes
for my granny.

91
00:08:12,880 --> 00:08:16,520
I can keep a secret, you know.

92
00:08:19,400 --> 00:08:24,360
You tell me one secret
you've ever kept.

93
00:08:24,360 --> 00:08:25,999
My granny keeps photographs.

94
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:27,599
In her dressing-table.

95
00:08:27,600 --> 00:08:28,640
You what?

96
00:08:28,880 --> 00:08:31,479
From the war Americans.

97
00:08:31,480 --> 00:08:33,239
And that's your secret, is it?

98
00:08:33,240 --> 00:08:33,800
Yes.

99
00:08:34,040 --> 00:08:35,679
Well, it's not any more,
you halfwit!

100
00:08:35,680 --> 00:08:37,679
You just told me.

101
00:08:37,680 --> 00:08:39,159
But you asked.

102
00:08:39,160 --> 00:08:41,799
Do you want to spend your whole
life being a complete eejit?

103
00:08:41,800 --> 00:08:46,040
No wonder your mammy buggered off.

104
00:08:49,200 --> 00:08:50,680
Oh, shit!

105
00:08:51,240 --> 00:08:52,560
Jimmy.

106
00:08:53,200 --> 00:08:55,079
Come on, back up here.

107
00:08:55,080 --> 00:08:56,519
Give me a hand

108
00:08:56,520 --> 00:08:57,920
Come on

109
00:09:01,880 --> 00:09:05,879
And listen don't you
tell your granny.

110
00:09:05,880 --> 00:09:09,879
Promise... Cross my heart.

111
00:09:09,880 --> 00:09:11,520
Yes.

112
00:09:16,560 --> 00:09:18,799
What is it?

113
00:09:18,800 --> 00:09:20,320
Treasure.

114
00:09:20,640 --> 00:09:22,999
The past, boy.

115
00:09:23,000 --> 00:09:24,520
The past.

116
00:10:04,280 --> 00:10:06,319
That's a Harvard.

117
00:10:06,320 --> 00:10:09,400
Here he comes.

118
00:10:14,480 --> 00:10:19,560
That's Jack.

119
00:10:21,360 --> 00:10:23,359
Is that your crazy father?

120
00:10:23,360 --> 00:10:24,719
It's a tradition, Marie.

121
00:10:24,720 --> 00:10:26,639
God, you're as stupid as he is.

122
00:10:26,640 --> 00:10:28,199
Flies beautiful, doesn't it?

123
00:10:28,200 --> 00:10:28,879
He could have killed us.

124
00:10:28,880 --> 00:10:30,319
He's not allowed to fly that low.

125
00:10:30,320 --> 00:10:31,799
Don't make a fuss, Marie.

126
00:10:31,800 --> 00:10:33,759
It's exactly what your daddy
would have wanted.

127
00:10:33,760 --> 00:10:34,439
Oh, really?

128
00:10:34,440 --> 00:10:37,279
Is he doing it for daddy,
or is he doing it to impress you?

129
00:10:37,280 --> 00:10:39,119
You don't know
what you're talking about.

130
00:10:39,120 --> 00:10:40,679
Is he coming around again?

131
00:10:40,680 --> 00:10:43,799
Oh, I certainly hope so.

132
00:10:43,800 --> 00:10:47,320
You should take this.

133
00:10:50,440 --> 00:10:53,079
There's a family trapped.

134
00:10:53,080 --> 00:10:53,560
That's it.

135
00:10:53,800 --> 00:10:56,920
One down, on the right.

136
00:10:58,760 --> 00:11:01,759
Michael Quinlan,
where in God's name have you been?!

137
00:11:01,760 --> 00:11:05,039
Get in that shelter right away!

138
00:11:05,040 --> 00:11:07,439
Everybody outside, come on. Run!

139
00:11:07,440 --> 00:11:07,920
Run!

140
00:11:08,160 --> 00:11:11,720
No messing about, come on!

141
00:11:14,560 --> 00:11:15,560
Eleanor.

142
00:11:15,840 --> 00:11:17,759
Didn't expect to find you here.

143
00:11:17,760 --> 00:11:19,919
Well, where did you
expect to find me?

144
00:11:19,920 --> 00:11:21,119
Not usually with us.

145
00:11:21,120 --> 00:11:24,559
In the Georgian Hotel with one of
your gentleman friends.

146
00:11:24,560 --> 00:11:27,359
I do more for the war effort
than you, Mrs Doyle.

147
00:11:27,360 --> 00:11:29,839
Making your woolly underwear
for the troops.

148
00:11:29,840 --> 00:11:34,560
And you taking it off fast
as they can put it on.

149
00:11:35,360 --> 00:11:37,079
Michael,
we missed you at evening Mass.

150
00:11:37,080 --> 00:11:38,399
You'd have got here
in time for a seat.

151
00:11:38,400 --> 00:11:39,280
Michael.

152
00:11:39,480 --> 00:11:41,359
You're a big lad now.

153
00:11:41,360 --> 00:11:44,119
Will you be joining the Army,
fighting for King and country?

154
00:11:44,120 --> 00:11:46,559
No, I'm gonna
be a fireman like my Da.

155
00:11:46,560 --> 00:11:47,599
You can sit here, Michael.

156
00:11:47,600 --> 00:11:48,519
Can I sit there?

157
00:11:48,520 --> 00:11:48,960
No.

158
00:11:49,200 --> 00:11:50,360
No.

159
00:11:50,600 --> 00:11:53,439
We can't possibly mix
both congregations, Michael.

160
00:11:53,440 --> 00:11:57,320
I'm forced to agree
with him there, Michael.

161
00:12:02,480 --> 00:12:03,320
Cathal?

162
00:12:03,560 --> 00:12:04,999
Sweet Jesus, is that you?

163
00:12:05,000 --> 00:12:06,479
You're taking a chance,
aren't you?

164
00:12:06,480 --> 00:12:08,559
Cathal, you'll
get yourself caught.

165
00:12:08,560 --> 00:12:09,999
They've put
a reward out for you.

166
00:12:10,000 --> 00:12:11,119
I don't care.

167
00:12:11,120 --> 00:12:11,880
Here.

168
00:12:12,080 --> 00:12:13,439
These are for you.

169
00:12:13,440 --> 00:12:16,800
Look, I had to see you.

170
00:12:18,600 --> 00:12:19,320
Eggs!

171
00:12:19,560 --> 00:12:21,119
Dear God in heaven!

172
00:12:21,120 --> 00:12:23,399
He has connections
over the border.

173
00:12:23,400 --> 00:12:26,559
I thought you were away fighting
for the other side, Cathal Thomas.

174
00:12:26,560 --> 00:12:27,199
He's right.

175
00:12:27,200 --> 00:12:28,719
It's a dangerous place for you.

176
00:12:28,720 --> 00:12:30,359
Is he fighting for the Germans?

177
00:12:30,360 --> 00:12:31,640
IRA.

178
00:12:31,800 --> 00:12:32,839
You should join us.

179
00:12:32,840 --> 00:12:33,839
Don't you dare.

180
00:12:33,840 --> 00:12:36,839
Thousands of good Catholic Irishmen
serving in the British Army,

181
00:12:36,840 --> 00:12:38,639
fighting against Fascism

182
00:12:38,640 --> 00:12:40,239
My son's one of them.

183
00:12:40,240 --> 00:12:43,279
And you... you're a damned traitor.

184
00:12:43,280 --> 00:12:43,760
Cathal.

185
00:12:43,960 --> 00:12:47,480
I say, hello,
are you all right in there?

186
00:12:48,280 --> 00:12:48,920
Hello?

187
00:12:49,160 --> 00:12:50,199
You all right in there?

188
00:12:50,200 --> 00:12:51,439
Cathal, no.

189
00:12:51,440 --> 00:12:51,920
Don't!

190
00:12:52,120 --> 00:12:53,439
We'll not say anything.

191
00:12:53,440 --> 00:12:54,839
If he's a policeman,
I'll kill him!

192
00:12:54,840 --> 00:12:55,599
He's a Brit.

193
00:12:55,600 --> 00:12:57,039
He's Army, not police, Cathal.

194
00:12:57,040 --> 00:12:57,919
He won't know you.

195
00:12:57,920 --> 00:12:58,559
Hold the door.

196
00:12:58,560 --> 00:13:00,839
Come on, Mr Cobb!

197
00:13:00,840 --> 00:13:01,480
Hurry up!

198
00:13:01,680 --> 00:13:02,400
Come on!

199
00:13:02,640 --> 00:13:03,160
Hello?

200
00:13:03,400 --> 00:13:06,640
The door is stuck.

201
00:13:06,920 --> 00:13:07,400
Don't.

202
00:13:07,640 --> 00:13:10,920
Don't say a word.

203
00:13:12,720 --> 00:13:13,240
Evening.

204
00:13:13,480 --> 00:13:14,399
Good evening, Officer.

205
00:13:14,400 --> 00:13:15,479
Everyone all right?

206
00:13:15,480 --> 00:13:16,400
Fine.

207
00:13:16,640 --> 00:13:18,319
We're fine.

208
00:13:18,320 --> 00:13:20,239
Do you think they've gone for
the night, sir?

209
00:13:20,240 --> 00:13:22,159
I think so, but there may be
some unexploded stuff.

210
00:13:22,160 --> 00:13:24,879
So best stay down here
till the all-clear

211
00:13:24,880 --> 00:13:26,159
Could you pass the word.

212
00:13:26,160 --> 00:13:28,039
We need an ambulance
in Market Street.

213
00:13:28,040 --> 00:13:29,679
Four casualties.

214
00:13:29,680 --> 00:13:32,760
I like your helmet.

215
00:13:33,360 --> 00:13:36,119
What on earth is this?

216
00:13:36,120 --> 00:13:39,440
Where did you get it?

217
00:13:39,920 --> 00:13:42,479
Bloody thing is loaded!

218
00:13:42,480 --> 00:13:44,559
Who gave this to you?

219
00:13:44,560 --> 00:13:46,559
You little idiot, Quinlan.

220
00:13:46,560 --> 00:13:47,959
What are you doing with that?

221
00:13:47,960 --> 00:13:49,159
Belonged to his old Da.

222
00:13:49,160 --> 00:13:50,559
From the last war.

223
00:13:50,560 --> 00:13:51,560
Souvenir.

224
00:13:51,800 --> 00:13:53,599
He'll scalp your arse, so he will.

225
00:13:53,600 --> 00:13:55,479
I've got to confiscate this.

226
00:13:55,480 --> 00:13:57,279
No need to tell the police,
though.

227
00:13:57,280 --> 00:13:58,719
Sure, he's only a wee lad.

228
00:13:58,720 --> 00:13:59,240
No.

229
00:13:59,440 --> 00:14:00,480
No need.

230
00:14:01,000 --> 00:14:03,159
Are the police up there now?

231
00:14:03,160 --> 00:14:04,359
The local boys?

232
00:14:04,360 --> 00:14:05,039
Afraid not.

233
00:14:05,040 --> 00:14:06,199
Just my chaps from the barracks.

234
00:14:06,200 --> 00:14:07,519
I'll come up and give you a hand.

235
00:14:07,520 --> 00:14:08,440
Thanks.

236
00:14:08,760 --> 00:14:10,440
Oh, Jesus.

237
00:14:10,640 --> 00:14:12,079
Get the hell out of here, Cathal.

238
00:14:12,080 --> 00:14:13,439
We should have given you up.

239
00:14:13,440 --> 00:14:17,640
You could have, but you didn't.

240
00:14:17,680 --> 00:14:21,040
None of you did.

241
00:14:21,920 --> 00:14:24,399
Is this what we're looking for,
Mr Quinlan?

242
00:14:24,400 --> 00:14:26,159
Just a piece of iron?

243
00:14:26,160 --> 00:14:27,560
Aluminium.

244
00:14:27,920 --> 00:14:29,439
From the fuselage.

245
00:14:29,440 --> 00:14:31,399
Or the wings, maybe.

246
00:14:31,400 --> 00:14:35,239
Biggest piece I ever found - B-17.

247
00:14:35,240 --> 00:14:36,559
You know what that is?

248
00:14:36,560 --> 00:14:37,160
Sure.

249
00:14:37,440 --> 00:14:38,479
It's a rock group.

250
00:14:38,480 --> 00:14:38,920
A band.

251
00:14:39,120 --> 00:14:41,679
It's not a bloody band.

252
00:14:41,680 --> 00:14:43,679
It's an airplane, you eejit.

253
00:14:43,680 --> 00:14:44,600
Oh, right.

254
00:14:44,840 --> 00:14:46,119
Crashed here.

255
00:14:46,120 --> 00:14:48,719
50 years ago.

256
00:14:48,720 --> 00:14:51,279
Ten people killed.

257
00:14:51,280 --> 00:14:54,479
Blown to bits.

258
00:14:54,480 --> 00:14:57,679
They've all forgotten,
but I remember.

259
00:14:57,680 --> 00:15:00,399
You remember it crashing?

260
00:15:00,400 --> 00:15:02,639
I heard it.

261
00:15:02,640 --> 00:15:04,759
I lived down the bottom,
Murray Street.

262
00:15:04,760 --> 00:15:05,800
Still do.

263
00:15:07,200 --> 00:15:09,359
What do you do this for,
Mr Quinlan?

264
00:15:09,360 --> 00:15:11,599
What are you looking for?

265
00:15:11,600 --> 00:15:13,479
Why should I be
looking for anything?

266
00:15:13,480 --> 00:15:15,839
Why do you dig all this up then?

267
00:15:15,840 --> 00:15:18,999
Just shut up and
give me a hand here.

268
00:15:19,000 --> 00:15:22,520
See if we can lift it.

269
00:15:38,120 --> 00:15:40,239
Hey, Ethel Ann, come on.

270
00:15:40,240 --> 00:15:44,159
But... okay.

271
00:15:44,160 --> 00:15:45,280
Wilbur?

272
00:15:45,520 --> 00:15:46,760
Oh, no.

273
00:16:03,840 --> 00:16:05,559
Okay, chocks in and checked.

274
00:16:05,560 --> 00:16:08,600
Come on out, sirs.

275
00:16:14,200 --> 00:16:16,679
That was the most incredible
thing I've ever done!

276
00:16:16,680 --> 00:16:18,399
Hello, fellas!

277
00:16:18,400 --> 00:16:19,639
That was fantastic.

278
00:16:19,640 --> 00:16:21,759
Jack, those B-17s are
just the greatest!

279
00:16:21,760 --> 00:16:22,919
It's a piece of cake to fly, too.

280
00:16:22,920 --> 00:16:23,799
Pilot showed us how.

281
00:16:23,800 --> 00:16:24,240
Oh, sure.

282
00:16:24,480 --> 00:16:25,439
You wanna take us up now then,
Chuck?

283
00:16:25,440 --> 00:16:25,960
You know.

284
00:16:26,160 --> 00:16:27,479
I feel like I could though,
you know.

285
00:16:27,480 --> 00:16:28,599
You look swell, Ethel Ann.

286
00:16:28,600 --> 00:16:29,679
Yeah, okay, come on.

287
00:16:29,680 --> 00:16:30,319
Who wants a soda?

288
00:16:30,320 --> 00:16:31,199
Let's go to Joe's.

289
00:16:31,200 --> 00:16:33,279
But I thought you all had classes?

290
00:16:33,280 --> 00:16:34,959
So, we skip one.

291
00:16:34,960 --> 00:16:36,519
You'll get in trouble.

292
00:16:36,520 --> 00:16:38,799
We're all gonna get in trouble,
there's a war coming!

293
00:16:38,800 --> 00:16:40,599
Yes, trouble!

294
00:16:40,600 --> 00:16:43,960
Big trouble!

295
00:16:55,000 --> 00:16:57,199
So, it's supposed to be
the final approach...

296
00:16:57,200 --> 00:16:59,199
...and we're thinking
something's wrong...

297
00:16:59,200 --> 00:17:03,359
We're flying at the runway at,
God, 200 knots!

298
00:17:03,360 --> 00:17:05,319
And the instructor says,

299
00:17:05,320 --> 00:17:08,159
"Well, buddy... " well

300
00:17:08,160 --> 00:17:10,159
...how about putting down
the flaps?".

301
00:17:10,160 --> 00:17:11,639
And the pilot goes,
"Oh, shoot!".

302
00:17:11,640 --> 00:17:12,080
And wham!

303
00:17:12,320 --> 00:17:13,519
Puts down the flaps,

304
00:17:13,520 --> 00:17:16,079
but he pulls back the stick
at the same time.

305
00:17:16,080 --> 00:17:18,159
That airplane must have been
standing straight on its tail.

306
00:17:18,160 --> 00:17:19,879
No, wait,
I saw you guys coming in.

307
00:17:19,880 --> 00:17:26,440
You were like that was me.

308
00:17:26,600 --> 00:17:28,719
Anybody want another soda?

309
00:17:28,720 --> 00:17:30,279
No, thank you.

310
00:17:30,280 --> 00:17:33,920
No, thanks, Jack.

311
00:17:40,680 --> 00:17:44,799
I wish I'd been up there with
you I really wanna fly.

312
00:17:44,800 --> 00:17:46,719
I don't think the Air Force
would like that.

313
00:17:46,720 --> 00:17:50,440
You got any cash?

314
00:17:52,440 --> 00:17:54,639
There's plenty of girl pilots.

315
00:17:54,640 --> 00:17:55,959
Amelia Earhart.

316
00:17:55,960 --> 00:17:56,840
Yeah.

317
00:17:57,120 --> 00:17:59,039
But not in a B-17.

318
00:17:59,040 --> 00:18:02,479
Not with a bunch of hairy
apes like us.

319
00:18:02,480 --> 00:18:04,079
So what about pilot school?

320
00:18:04,080 --> 00:18:04,919
Still going?

321
00:18:04,920 --> 00:18:05,839
I don't know.

322
00:18:05,840 --> 00:18:09,639
The other guys are okay,
but I got problems with math.

323
00:18:09,640 --> 00:18:11,879
They won't stop me
from going up there.

324
00:18:11,880 --> 00:18:13,799
Bombardier, gunner.

325
00:18:13,800 --> 00:18:15,119
I don't care.

326
00:18:15,120 --> 00:18:17,999
Nor do I,
so long as you're happy.

327
00:18:18,000 --> 00:18:19,240
I'm happy.

328
00:18:19,760 --> 00:18:23,480
I've never been so happy.

329
00:18:23,640 --> 00:18:25,599
Seems the whole town is
in love with that girl.

330
00:18:25,600 --> 00:18:27,959
Never thought she'd choose
the country boy.

331
00:18:27,960 --> 00:18:28,799
Country boy?

332
00:18:28,800 --> 00:18:29,839
I trust him with my life.

333
00:18:29,840 --> 00:18:31,919
Don't worry, my lips are sealed.

334
00:18:31,920 --> 00:18:35,319
Young love, huh?

335
00:18:35,320 --> 00:18:36,600
Come on.

336
00:18:36,880 --> 00:18:39,119
One hamburger and three fries.

337
00:18:39,120 --> 00:18:39,720
Chuck

338
00:18:42,480 --> 00:18:45,839
Come on, lover boy.

339
00:18:45,840 --> 00:18:49,360
Come on, guys.

340
00:19:19,920 --> 00:19:20,520
Marie.

341
00:19:20,760 --> 00:19:22,160
Marie?

342
00:19:22,360 --> 00:19:23,359
I guess you upset her.

343
00:19:23,360 --> 00:19:26,640
Not hard to do.

344
00:19:28,080 --> 00:19:29,879
Stupid tune.

345
00:19:29,880 --> 00:19:32,239
Oh, come on,
they were great tunes.

346
00:19:32,240 --> 00:19:33,999
I need a drink.

347
00:19:34,000 --> 00:19:36,399
Steady, you've had a few already.

348
00:19:36,400 --> 00:19:37,000
Why not?

349
00:19:37,240 --> 00:19:38,999
I can have anything I want now.

350
00:19:39,000 --> 00:19:39,640
Yeah.

351
00:19:39,880 --> 00:19:41,199
What do you want, Ethel?

352
00:19:41,200 --> 00:19:42,080
Go inside.

353
00:19:45,520 --> 00:19:47,759
Well, at least let me
get the door for you.

354
00:19:47,760 --> 00:19:50,439
I can get the door, thank you.

355
00:19:50,440 --> 00:19:52,959
I've lived here long enough.

356
00:19:52,960 --> 00:19:56,240
Well, just as you please.

357
00:20:05,000 --> 00:20:06,319
This house.

358
00:20:06,320 --> 00:20:07,360
Yeah.

359
00:20:07,720 --> 00:20:10,079
Does seem kind of strange,
doesn't it?

360
00:20:10,080 --> 00:20:12,759
Coming back to the house that he
built without him in it.

361
00:20:12,760 --> 00:20:14,120
Yes.

362
00:20:14,960 --> 00:20:16,320
Sure.

363
00:20:16,560 --> 00:20:18,639
Jack, thank you for
the air raid and all.

364
00:20:18,640 --> 00:20:19,919
My pleasure, girl.

365
00:20:19,920 --> 00:20:21,519
Scared me half to death.

366
00:20:21,520 --> 00:20:22,759
You ought to lose your licence.

367
00:20:22,760 --> 00:20:24,359
Yeah, that's what the Sheriff said.

368
00:20:24,360 --> 00:20:26,279
But I told him it was
an old tradition.

369
00:20:26,280 --> 00:20:28,079
Class of June '42.

370
00:20:28,080 --> 00:20:29,479
Go home, Jack.

371
00:20:29,480 --> 00:20:31,279
What do you mean, now?

372
00:20:31,280 --> 00:20:32,360
Yes, now.

373
00:20:32,760 --> 00:20:34,639
Come on, dad.

374
00:20:34,640 --> 00:20:35,920
Okay.

375
00:20:38,800 --> 00:20:40,119
You won't forget
to do something for me,

376
00:20:40,120 --> 00:20:41,279
will you, Ethel?

377
00:20:41,280 --> 00:20:42,879
What's that?

378
00:20:42,880 --> 00:20:44,320
Grieve.

379
00:20:48,760 --> 00:20:51,599
Your father's picture
at the Air Academy.

380
00:20:51,600 --> 00:20:53,199
Put it back, please.

381
00:20:53,200 --> 00:20:54,360
Sorry.

382
00:21:01,440 --> 00:21:04,079
You never talk about those times.

383
00:21:04,080 --> 00:21:05,279
Neither did dad.

384
00:21:05,280 --> 00:21:05,880
No.

385
00:21:06,120 --> 00:21:07,599
Did you know a lot of these boys?

386
00:21:07,600 --> 00:21:10,079
Yes, they were
a great bunch of guys.

387
00:21:10,080 --> 00:21:11,599
We had some good times.

388
00:21:11,600 --> 00:21:13,999
Could you tell me about it?

389
00:21:14,000 --> 00:21:17,039
Could you tell me about them?

390
00:21:17,040 --> 00:21:19,159
What you want to know
is whether I did it

391
00:21:19,160 --> 00:21:20,759
with one of them and which one.

392
00:21:20,760 --> 00:21:21,200
No.

393
00:21:21,440 --> 00:21:23,639
Well, why not?

394
00:21:23,640 --> 00:21:26,319
It's notjust a picture,
they were flesh and blood.

395
00:21:26,320 --> 00:21:29,599
Okay, just forget it.

396
00:21:29,600 --> 00:21:31,279
Have you been with Pete yet?

397
00:21:31,280 --> 00:21:31,800
What?

398
00:21:32,040 --> 00:21:32,999
Jack's boy, Pete.

399
00:21:33,000 --> 00:21:34,359
Have you been with him yet?

400
00:21:34,360 --> 00:21:35,439
Mom, what has gotten into you?

401
00:21:35,440 --> 00:21:37,519
How much have you been drinking?

402
00:21:37,520 --> 00:21:40,879
Time you got something
for yourself, Marie.

403
00:21:40,880 --> 00:21:43,359
Life is passing you by.

404
00:21:43,360 --> 00:21:44,719
Peter is a nice guy.

405
00:21:44,720 --> 00:21:49,400
I'm just not ready.

406
00:21:49,680 --> 00:21:55,759
But you must never,
ever let a man build you a house.

407
00:21:55,760 --> 00:21:56,240
No.

408
00:21:56,480 --> 00:21:58,959
As long as you stay there,
he'll stay with you.

409
00:21:58,960 --> 00:22:06,800
You may try to hide him
but he'll be there, inside it.

410
00:22:09,320 --> 00:22:11,919
Why don't you try it with Peter?

411
00:22:11,920 --> 00:22:14,519
Would you stop talking about sex?

412
00:22:14,520 --> 00:22:16,879
You shouldn't be thinking about
that right now.

413
00:22:16,880 --> 00:22:17,320
Really?

414
00:22:17,520 --> 00:22:19,599
Well, what the hell else
should I be thinking about?

415
00:22:19,600 --> 00:22:22,159
Daddy! We just buried him!

416
00:22:22,160 --> 00:22:22,760
Yes.

417
00:22:23,040 --> 00:22:24,040
Right.

418
00:22:25,760 --> 00:22:31,040
I guess this means I won't be
getting any any more, huh?

419
00:22:33,040 --> 00:22:35,519
I'm sorry, sweetheart.

420
00:22:35,520 --> 00:22:36,880
Me, too.

421
00:22:38,240 --> 00:22:42,280
Your father was a fine man.

422
00:22:42,640 --> 00:22:45,359
I guess I should be
grateful to him.

423
00:22:45,360 --> 00:22:46,720
Grateful?

424
00:22:49,800 --> 00:22:53,599
The boys at the Academy I didn't.

425
00:22:53,600 --> 00:22:57,400
I mean, it wasn't like that.

426
00:23:00,600 --> 00:23:03,759
I was faithful.

427
00:23:03,760 --> 00:23:11,159
I was always always,
always, always faithful.

428
00:23:11,160 --> 00:23:15,520
So, how do you say three
I's in Spanish?

429
00:23:17,720 --> 00:23:18,760
I, ya, ya.

430
00:23:23,280 --> 00:23:24,719
It's so big.

431
00:23:24,720 --> 00:23:26,919
He had his cousins
helping him over the winter.

432
00:23:26,920 --> 00:23:30,719
But they're back at the farm now,
so we're helping him finish it.

433
00:23:30,720 --> 00:23:31,840
That's it.

434
00:23:32,080 --> 00:23:32,799
Good morning.

435
00:23:32,800 --> 00:23:33,240
Morning.

436
00:23:33,480 --> 00:23:34,319
Teddy around?

437
00:23:34,320 --> 00:23:35,199
Back at the house.

438
00:23:35,200 --> 00:23:36,640
Thank you.

439
00:23:56,080 --> 00:23:58,359
It's beautiful.

440
00:23:58,360 --> 00:24:01,199
He's sure been working hard.

441
00:24:01,200 --> 00:24:02,240
Hey!

442
00:24:02,640 --> 00:24:04,159
I wasn't expecting you so soon.

443
00:24:04,160 --> 00:24:06,159
I fell asleep upstairs.

444
00:24:06,160 --> 00:24:08,399
You've framed out
the upstairs already?

445
00:24:08,400 --> 00:24:12,519
Sure have, I there's
so much more to do though.

446
00:24:12,520 --> 00:24:14,399
Could you guys help me
bring up the latest delivery?

447
00:24:14,400 --> 00:24:15,359
That pile up by the road?

448
00:24:15,360 --> 00:24:16,280
Yeah.

449
00:24:16,480 --> 00:24:17,320
Sure

450
00:24:17,520 --> 00:24:19,439
Yeah, we can do that for you.

451
00:24:19,440 --> 00:24:21,439
Come on, Chuck.

452
00:24:21,440 --> 00:24:23,159
Jack, these are my best clothes.

453
00:24:23,160 --> 00:24:24,440
Come on.

454
00:24:26,280 --> 00:24:29,079
How come you've told me
so little about this place?

455
00:24:29,080 --> 00:24:30,799
It's no secret.

456
00:24:30,800 --> 00:24:32,639
Where did you
get the money for it?

457
00:24:32,640 --> 00:24:35,039
My dad left
me this piece of land.

458
00:24:35,040 --> 00:24:36,799
A little cash.

459
00:24:36,800 --> 00:24:41,719
I worked in a sawmill last summer,
and they they paid me in lumber.

460
00:24:41,720 --> 00:24:45,360
I wanna look upstairs.

461
00:24:45,760 --> 00:24:48,559
I thought you told me you were
away getting an education?

462
00:24:48,560 --> 00:24:50,079
That was it, I guess.

463
00:24:50,080 --> 00:24:51,479
I read books, too.

464
00:24:51,480 --> 00:24:52,999
Place is solid.

465
00:24:53,000 --> 00:24:54,159
Building up to a standard,

466
00:24:54,160 --> 00:24:56,119
not down to a price,
is what the lumber guy said.

467
00:24:56,120 --> 00:24:57,759
Oh, I'll bet he did.

468
00:24:57,760 --> 00:25:00,520
Hey, buzzard.

469
00:25:01,200 --> 00:25:05,159
He's around here all the time
Keeps me company.

470
00:25:05,160 --> 00:25:06,839
You've almost moved in.

471
00:25:06,840 --> 00:25:07,840
Yeah.

472
00:25:08,720 --> 00:25:10,719
I may be running out of time.

473
00:25:10,720 --> 00:25:12,319
What do you mean?

474
00:25:12,320 --> 00:25:15,159
The war I guess.

475
00:25:15,160 --> 00:25:17,039
So it's gonna come, then?

476
00:25:17,040 --> 00:25:21,200
That's why we all
joined the Air Academy.

477
00:25:22,000 --> 00:25:23,999
Why are you doing all this?

478
00:25:24,000 --> 00:25:26,399
Your folks wouldn't
like me one bit.

479
00:25:26,400 --> 00:25:31,199
But when I do ask them,
I've gotta have something I can show.

480
00:25:31,200 --> 00:25:34,079
Something I can give you.

481
00:25:34,080 --> 00:25:36,159
You're building this house for me?

482
00:25:36,160 --> 00:25:37,999
If I get into the Air Force

483
00:25:38,000 --> 00:25:39,999
become a Sergeant maybe, then

484
00:25:40,000 --> 00:25:41,959
that'd be something.

485
00:25:41,960 --> 00:25:45,199
And then I could ask your folks.

486
00:25:45,200 --> 00:25:49,040
I'd be some kind of gentleman.

487
00:25:49,160 --> 00:25:51,839
You are a gentleman, Teddy.

488
00:25:51,840 --> 00:25:55,199
I sure don't smell like one just now.

489
00:25:55,200 --> 00:25:57,039
Let me try.

490
00:25:57,040 --> 00:25:58,360
Excuse me?

491
00:25:59,440 --> 00:26:01,159
Let me smell you.

492
00:26:01,160 --> 00:26:04,079
Are you kidding?

493
00:26:04,080 --> 00:26:05,480
No.

494
00:26:07,680 --> 00:26:10,439
I wanna remember you.

495
00:26:10,440 --> 00:26:14,440
Just as you are now.

496
00:26:18,840 --> 00:26:22,800
Don't move.

497
00:26:32,200 --> 00:26:37,439
I wanna remember
this moment all my life.

498
00:26:37,440 --> 00:26:38,839
Teddy, Ethel Ann?

499
00:26:38,840 --> 00:26:40,160
No.

500
00:26:42,560 --> 00:26:44,120
Teddy?

501
00:26:46,640 --> 00:26:51,040
Come on, Chuck... Let's go.

502
00:27:32,080 --> 00:27:35,840
You're so beautiful.

503
00:28:00,320 --> 00:28:02,319
Sometimes I can still smell it.

504
00:28:02,320 --> 00:28:03,040
What?

505
00:28:03,280 --> 00:28:04,919
Aviation fuel.

506
00:28:04,920 --> 00:28:06,599
That was 50 years ago.

507
00:28:06,600 --> 00:28:07,999
And you said it burnt.

508
00:28:08,000 --> 00:28:10,079
Some soaked into the ground,
maybe.

509
00:28:10,080 --> 00:28:12,119
I can't smell it,
but, look, I found this.

510
00:28:12,120 --> 00:28:15,040
What is it?

511
00:28:16,800 --> 00:28:18,519
Granny says
I shouldn't mix with you.

512
00:28:18,520 --> 00:28:20,439
You promised me
you wouldn't tell her.

513
00:28:20,440 --> 00:28:22,239
She says you're worse
than a Protestant.

514
00:28:22,240 --> 00:28:23,479
What's worse than a Protestant?

515
00:28:23,480 --> 00:28:26,239
An atheist.

516
00:28:26,240 --> 00:28:28,799
Mr Quinlan, what we're doing,
is it illegal?

517
00:28:28,800 --> 00:28:29,840
Probably.

518
00:28:30,800 --> 00:28:33,599
Only there's a man over there.

519
00:28:33,600 --> 00:28:36,879
Do we stop digging?

520
00:28:36,880 --> 00:28:38,919
Turn away, don't look at him.

521
00:28:38,920 --> 00:28:41,279
He'll not bother us.

522
00:28:41,280 --> 00:28:43,479
You took your time, Cathal.

523
00:28:43,480 --> 00:28:45,519
Mr Thomas to you

524
00:28:45,520 --> 00:28:47,799
There was no need
for you to be here.

525
00:28:47,800 --> 00:28:50,639
Just an observer.

526
00:28:50,640 --> 00:28:53,959
Do they think I can't
run my own operation?

527
00:28:53,960 --> 00:28:55,439
Why did they change the target?

528
00:28:55,440 --> 00:28:57,959
Wouldn't want to
lose support community.

529
00:28:57,960 --> 00:29:00,879
And we have interests in that area.

530
00:29:00,880 --> 00:29:04,839
You mean you're
selling drugs there.

531
00:29:04,840 --> 00:29:07,039
Beautiful view

532
00:29:07,040 --> 00:29:08,679
Who is the old man?

533
00:29:08,680 --> 00:29:10,319
He's digging up an airplane.

534
00:29:10,320 --> 00:29:11,519
It crashed here.

535
00:29:11,520 --> 00:29:13,439
And you let him do it?

536
00:29:13,440 --> 00:29:16,079
I know him.

537
00:29:16,080 --> 00:29:19,999
Digging on Black Mountain
is a bad idea.

538
00:29:20,000 --> 00:29:22,799
Never know what you'll find.

539
00:29:22,800 --> 00:29:24,719
What I gave you, what is it?

540
00:29:24,720 --> 00:29:26,039
It's very good.

541
00:29:26,040 --> 00:29:28,239
A switch... Radio, maybe.

542
00:29:28,240 --> 00:29:29,080
Intercom.

543
00:29:29,320 --> 00:29:32,079
I'll get it home,
do some research.

544
00:29:32,080 --> 00:29:33,839
I found that, you know

545
00:29:33,840 --> 00:29:37,400
By rights it's mine.

546
00:29:38,200 --> 00:29:39,919
Shankhill Road.

547
00:29:39,920 --> 00:29:41,040
Yes.

548
00:29:43,320 --> 00:29:45,119
You're an atheist then?

549
00:29:45,120 --> 00:29:47,039
You don't believe in God and

550
00:29:47,040 --> 00:29:49,479
the Blessed Virgin Mary
and all that stuff?

551
00:29:49,480 --> 00:29:50,440
No.

552
00:29:50,680 --> 00:29:51,560
Why not?

553
00:29:51,800 --> 00:29:55,919
30 years of being
